such as Thomas Charles Farrer and John Henry Hill championed a new style of landscape painting characterized by vibrant palettes, antipicturesque compositions, and meticulous brushwork. Their radicalism, however, was not solely one of style. Sophie Lynford traces how the American Pre-Raphaelites proclaimed themselves catalysts of a wide-ranging reform movement that staged politically motivated interventions in multiple cultural arenas, from architecture and criticism to collecting, exhibition design, and higher education. She examines how they publicly rejected their prominent contemporaries, the artists known as the Hudson River School, and how they offered incisive critiques of antebellum society by importing British models of landscape theory and practice.Beautifully illustrated and drawing on a wealth of archival material, Painting Dissent transforms our understanding of how American artists depicted the nation during the most turbulent decades of the nineteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aPainting, Americany19th century. 0aPre-RaphaelitismzUnited States. 7aART / Art & Politics.2bisacsh  aAbolitionism.  aAdmiration.  aArticles of organization.  aBehalf.  aCalculation.  aCareer.  aCatastrophism.  aCharles Dickens.  aClassical liberalism.  aCollegiate Gothic.  aConstant Troyon.  aCorn Laws.  aCrayon.  aCurriculum.  aDepiction.  aDepth of field.  aEconomic freedom.  aEconomic nationalism.  aEmpiricism.  aEssay.  aEssentialism.  aFord Madox Brown.  aFront organization.  aGeologist.  aGeorge School.  aGothic Revival architecture.  aGothic architecture.  aGustave de Molinari.  aHarvard University.  aHoughton Library.  aHudson River.  aHydrotherapy.  aImagery.  aInstrumentalism.  aInternational trade.  aJ. Paul Getty Museum.  aJoh